K{\footnote K  options}
\keepn \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i \f12 [2.1] Command line parameters\par \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \fi-792 \li792 \f12 \b \i \cf0 Note\b0 \i0 :\tab The command-line options of WinDEU are just for compatibility with DEU. WinDEU allows the change of nearly all these parameters in the new preferences dialog box, but for the current session only.\par \par  \b \i Note\b0 \i0 :\tab The effect of the Boolean options (i, s0, ...) may be reversed by using a '+' instead of a '-'.  For example, '+i' means 'no info bar'.\par \par -help\par \fi0 \li396 View command line options without entering WinDEU.\par \pard \par -a\tab (-addselbox)\par \li396 Additive selection box.  Objects will be added to the current selection (when you use the selection box) instead of replacing the current selection by what is in the box.\par \pard \tx1080 \fi-720 \li1116 \b \i Note\b0 \i0 :\tab With WinDEU, you can easily use an additive selection box with the SHIFT key, so this option is now obsolete. See \uldb Mouse Commands\uldb0 \v MOUSE_COMMANDS\v0 \par \pard \par \fi-396 \li396  -d\tab (-debug)\par \fi0 Debug mode.  Will produce a log file of warning messages to help track down LineDefs that have problems.  The number of the bad LineDefs will be listed.  This file will be called "\f1 WINDEU.LOG\f12 ". The log file will also have timestamps.\par \pard \par \fi-396 \li396  -e\tab (-expert)\par \fi0 Expert mode.  Doesn't ask for confirmation of some operations (e.g. deleting an object or rebuilding the Nodes).\par \pard \par i   (infobar)\par \li396 Display the info bar in the level editor.\par \pard \par q   (quiet)\par \li396 QUIET! suppresses the sound made when you select or mark an object.  Use it if you're in a library :)\par \pard \par qq   (quieter)\par \li396 QUIET^2!  Complete silence.  WinDEU will not make any sound, not even for warnings. Enjoy the Silence...\par \pard \par z <zoom>   (zoom)\par \li396 ZOOM.  Specify initial zoom setting.\par \pard \par c   (color2)\par \li396 Use the alternate color set for displaying the Things.\par \pard \par w <main wad file>   (main)\par \li396 Specify name of main wad file (e.g. DOOM.WAD).\par \pard \par file <pwad, pwad, ...>\par \li396 Load patch WAD file(s), just like with DOOM. Note: Patch wad files may also be loaded from the "File" menu.\par \pard \par pw <pwad>   (pwad)\par \li396 Add ONE patch file to be loaded.\par \pard \par sf   (splitfactor)\par \li396 Adjust scale on the nodes builder.  This parameter is for those techie types that like to fiddle with things.  There is no need for the average user to worry about this parameter.  (The default value of 8 is the same value that id software uses.  A number less than 8 means "more balanced" and a number higher than 8 means "least splits".  Use this parameter at your own risk.  We recommend the default value of 8.) \par \pard \par s0   (select0)\par \li396 Select object 0 when switching modes.\par \pard \par config <ini file>\par \li396 Specify an alternate DEU configuration file other than WinDEU.INI\par \par \pard 3d\tab (3dcontrols)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Don't use the 3D controls style in the dialog boxes.  This looks better, but you need a dll.\par See \uldb Installing WindDEU\uldb0 \v Installing_WindDEU\v0 \par \pard \par dl (drawlength)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Draw the moving LineDefs length in Vertexes and LineDefs editing mode.\par \pard \par bp (buildpriority)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Set the priority of the nodes builder when rebuilding a level. This priority determines the minimum number of milliseconds the builder will compute before giving control back to Windows. If you set 20, it means WinDEU will gives back control to Windows approximately (at most) 50 times a second. Since this setting is independant of your CPU speed, you shouldn't use a value too small is your CPU is slow. For example, Using a BuildPriority of 1ms with a 386SX16 will increase the overhead of multi-tasking and the nodes builder will be slow.\par \pard \par mu (maxundo)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Set the maximum number of UNDO/REDO entries in the level editor. Each UNDO entry takes as much memory as the map objects, so don't be too genererous about this one. The default value is 5.\par \pard \par gs (gridsize)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Set the initial grid size of the level editor. Legal values are 0, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256. Default value is 8.\par \pard \par sg (showgrid)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Set the initial "show grid" option in the level editor. Be default, the grid is not shown when entering the editor.\par \pard \par ng (snaptogrid)\par \li360 *** WinDEU NEW ***\par \li396 Set the initial snap to grid option in the level editor. Be default, the "snap to grid" option is off when entering the editor.\par \pard \par See also \uldb Preference Settings\uldb0 \v PREFERENCES\v0 , \uldb Initialization file WinDEU.INI\uldb0 \v WINDEU_INI\v0 \par \f10 \par \page
