\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i About WinDEU\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Brief information about the WinDEU and DEU programmers and the contributed work from the net.\par \par The logo picture of WinDEU 5.24 has been drawn by CalvnHobs1@aol.com. Thanks to him!\par \par The Info button opens a new dialog box with detailed version information of WinDEU. This dialog box displays a "Build time", which identifies the WinDEU version. When reporting a WinDEU bug, try to include this build time, so that I can identify what version of WinDEU you are using.\par \par \page
${\footnote $ [5] Wad file description}
#{\footnote # WAD_FILE}
+{\footnote + 00006}
K{\footnote K Wad file, description of}
K{\footnote K Description of WAD files}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5] Wad file description\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 WinDEU works by editing the database that DOOM uses to store its information about each of the levels.  These database files are called WAD files.  There are two types of WAD files.\par \par \b IWAD File\b0 :\par \par \pard \tx0 \tx396 \tx792 \tx1188 \tx1584 \tx1980 \tx2376 \tx2778 \tx3174 \tx3570 \tx3966 \tx4362 \tx4758 \tx5154 \tx5556 \tx5952 \tx6348 \tx6744 \tx7140 \li396 This is the main data base file. It contains all the information about the graphics, sound, level maps, etc of the game.  There is only one IWAD file called DOOM.WAD and it must be in the current directory when DOOM is run.\par \li0 \par \b PWAD File\b0 :\par \par \li396 This is a special patch of the IWAD file.  It contains updates about the IWAD file.  PWAD files created by DEU will contain an updated map of a game level. PWAD files can be called anything.  When running DOOM, DOOM must be told to load a PWAD file.  This is done with the FILE parameter.  PWAD files are small so they can be easily shared.\par \pard \par \page
${\footnote $ [5.1] Description of Vertices}
#{\footnote # VERTICES_DESCR}
+{\footnote + AM:00001}
K{\footnote K Vertices, description of}
K{\footnote K Description of Vertices}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5.1] Description of Vertices\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \cf5 \fs24 \pard \f12 \cf1 Vertices are simply points.  Each vertex has an x,y coordinate on a map. DOOM maps are 2 dimension so there is no z coordinate.  Vertices are used as the starting and ending points of \uldb LineDefs\uldb0 \v LINEDEFS_DESCR\v0 .\par \f10 \par \page
${\footnote $ [5.2] Description of LineDefs}
#{\footnote # LINEDEFS_DESCR}
+{\footnote + AM:00002}
K{\footnote K LineDefs, description of}
K{\footnote K  Description of LineDefs}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5.2] Description of LineDefs\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Lines which define boundaries in the map. These boundaries define the borders of a sector or the location of a trigger that you walk across. Each LineDef has a starting \uldb vertex\uldb0 \v VERTICES_DESCR\v0  and and ending vertex. There is a first and second side to every LineDef. Either side may have a reference to a \uldb SideDef\uldb0 \v SIDEDEFS_DESCR\v0 . LineDefs are also what is used as triggers and/or switches for special \uldb sectors\uldb0 \v SECTORS_DESCR\v0 .\par \par See also:\par \tab \uldb [5.6] Attributes of LineDefs\uldb0 \v LINEDEF_ATTRIBUTES\v0 \par \tab \uldb [5.7] Types of LineDefs\uldb0 \v Types_of_LineDefs\v0 \par \tab \uldb [5.8] Normal, Upper, Lower textures\uldb0 \v NOUPLO_TEXTURES\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ [5.3] Description of SideDefs}
#{\footnote # SIDEDEFS_DESCR}
+{\footnote + AM:00003}
K{\footnote K SideDefs, description of}
K{\footnote K  Description of SideDefs}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5.3] Description of SideDefs\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \cf5 \fs24 \pard \f12 \cf1 Every visible side of a \uldb LineDef\uldb0 \v LINEDEFS_DESCR\v0  must have a SideDef. The SideDefs are used to put wall textures on. (See \uldb description of upper/lower/normal textures\uldb0 \v NOUPLO_TEXTURES\v0  below.)  An enclosed set of SideDefs is what defines a \uldb Sector\uldb0 \v SECTORS_DESCR\v0 .\par \f10 \par \page
${\footnote $ [5.4] Description of Sectors}
#{\footnote # SECTORS_DESCR}
+{\footnote + AM:00004}
K{\footnote K Sectors, description of}
K{\footnote K  Description of Sectors}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5.4] Description of Sectors\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 A Sector is made up of a group of 3 or more enclosed \uldb SideDefs\uldb0 \v SIDEDEFS_DESCR\v0 .  A sector can be viewed as a room or an area within a room.  Sectors contain ceiling and floor height information, ceiling and floor textures, special sector information (does it hurt to be there?  did you find a secret if you enter?)  Sectors are the only structure that "moves" in DOOM.  Lifts, Staircases, Doors, are all specially defined sectors. See also \uldb [6] Special Doom areas\uldb0 \v SPECIAL_DOOM_AREAS\v0 \par \f10 \par \page
