${\footnote $ [5.6] Attributes of LineDefs}
#{\footnote # LINEDEF_ATTRIBUTES}
+{\footnote + AM:00006}
K{\footnote K LineDefs, Attributes}
K{\footnote K  Attributes of LineDefs}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5.6] Attributes of LineDefs\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Some abbreviations have been used for the \uldb LineDef\uldb0 \v LINEDEFS_DESCR\v0  attributes:\par \par \b Flag\tab Bit\tab Description\par \fi-1440 \li1440 \b0 Im\tab 0\tab Impassible by players and monsters.\par Mo\tab 1\tab Monsters cannot cross this line.\par 2S\tab 2\tab Twosided wall/may shoot through.\par Up\tab 3\tab Upper texture is "unpegged".  Try it with moving ceilings or doors.\par Lo\tab 4\tab Lower texture is "unpegged".  Try it with moving floors or lifts.\par Se\tab 5\tab Secret.  This line appears as normal on the map.\par So\tab 6\tab Blocks sound.  The sounds won't travel past this line.\par Ma\tab 7\tab Invisible on the map.  Even with the "computer map" powerup.\par In\tab 8\tab Already on the map at startup. \par \pard \tx0 \tx396 \tx792 \tx1188 \tx1584 \tx1980 \tx2376 \tx2778 \tx3174 \tx3570 \tx3966 \tx4362 \tx4758 \tx5154 \tx5556 \tx5952 \tx6348 \tx6744 \tx7140 \f10 \par \page
${\footnote $ [5.7] Types of LineDefs}
#{\footnote # Types_of_LineDefs}
+{\footnote + AM:00007}
K{\footnote K LineDefs, types}
K{\footnote K  Types of LineDefs}
\keepn \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i \f12 [5.7] Types of LineDefs\par \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 The first two letters in each \uldb LineDef\uldb0 \v LINEDEFS_DESCR\v0  type give its features.\par The first letter may be:\par \par \fi-1440 \li1440 D\tab Door\tab Press the spacebar to open it.\par S\tab Switch\tab Press the spacebar to activate this LineDef.\par W\tab Walk\tab Walk across this LineDef to activate it.\par G\tab Gun\tab You need to shoot that LineDef to activate it.\par \pard \par Except for doors ("D") and the "end level" LineDefs, all linedefs that activate a sector need a "Sector tag" number and at least one Sector with the same tag number to operate.\par \par The second letter may be:\par \par \fi-1440 \li1440 R\tab Repeatable.\par 1\tab Works only once.\par \pard \par Abbreviations are also used in the type name.  They refer to what happens to the Sector when triggered by this LineDef:\par \par \fi-1440 \li1440 O\tab Stays Open\par \fi0 \li396  Used only for doors.\par \pard \par \fi-1440 \li1440 N\tab Neighbor\par \fi0 \li396 Usually, this means that the floor rises or  lowers until it reaches the floor height of an adjacent  sector on its way.  In the menus, I have used "Ne." instead.\par \pard \par \fi-1440 \li1440 T\tab Texture and Type change\par \fi0 \li396 Same as above, but the texture and  type of the Sector are also changed.  The new Sector floor texture and type are copied from the Sector where the switch or walkthough LineDef is, not from the adjacent Sector(s).\par \pard \par \fi-1440 \li1440 C\tab Ceiling\par \fi0 \li396 This means that the floor rises until it reaches  the ceiling height of one adjacent Sector.\par \pard \par <,>\par \li396 Used as modifiers for the above letters.  "<N" means that  the floor will stop just below a neighboring floor.\par \pard \f10 \par \page
${\footnote $ [5.8] Normal, Upper, Lower textures}
#{\footnote # NOUPLO_TEXTURES}
+{\footnote + AM:00008}
K{\footnote K Normal, Upper, Lower textures}
K{\footnote K  Textures, Normal, Upper, Lower}
K{\footnote K  Wall textures}
K{\footnote K  SideDefs textures}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [5.8] Normal, Upper, Lower textures\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 These are the three parts of a SideDef.\par \par \pard \tx756 \fi-360 \li756 1.\tab Upper Texture is used to account for variations in ceiling height. The SideDef facing the sector with the higher ceiling must have an upper texture defined.\par \pard \par \pard \tx756 \fi-360 \li756 2.\tab Lower Texture accounts for variations in floor height.  The SideDef of a line that faces a sector with a lower floor height must have a lower texture defined.\par \pard \par \pard \tx756 \fi-360 \li756 3.\tab \tab The Normal Texture is used for the surface of the sidedef which is below the ceiling height and above the floor height.\par \pard \fi-792 \li792 \par \fi-720 \li720 \b \i Note\b0 \i0 :\tab The LineDef/SideDef editor displays upper/lower texture boxes in RED if they are transparent and shouldn't be.  They will be grey if they are not visible and should be left transparent. If they are visible they will be black (transparent or not).  This is very helpful in eliminating the \uldb Hall of Mirrors (HOM) effect\uldb0 \v HOM_EFFECT\v0  caused by missing texture assignments.\par \pard \par \page
${\footnote $ [6] Special Doom areas}
#{\footnote # SPECIAL_DOOM_AREAS}
+{\footnote + 00007}
K{\footnote K Special Doom areas}
K{\footnote K  Areas, special}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [6] Special Doom areas\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Tag numbers are used to uniquely identity a structure within the level.  There are tag numbers for both sectors and for linedefs. For example, if a switch is used to activate a Sector, then both this Sector and the LineDef with the switch will have the same\par tag number.\par \par See also:\par \tab \uldb Doors\uldb0 \v DOORS\v0 \par \tab \uldb Lifts\uldb0 \v LIFTS\v0 \par \tab \uldb Teleporters\uldb0 \v TELEPORTERS\v0 \par \tab \uldb Rising stairs\uldb0 \v RISING_STAIRS\v0 \par \tab \uldb Secret areas\uldb0 \v SECRET_AREAS\v0 \par \tab \uldb Standard rooms\uldb0 \v STANDARD_ROOMS\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ [6.1] Doors}
#{\footnote # DOORS}
+{\footnote + AN:00001}
K{\footnote K Doors}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [6.1] Doors\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 A door is a Sector which usually starts with its ceiling at that same height as its floor (door closed).  When the player presses the spacebar, the ceiling will rise, opening the door.  On both sides of the door, you need one of the "D" LineDefs types.  You don't need to give a tag number to the Sector or the LineDefs.\par \par If you want to be able to open this door with a switch, then you need to give the same tag number to the Sector and the switch. Pick any number that is not used by another LineDef or Sector.\par \par \b Front and Back sides of Door\b0 :\par \par \li396 The lines that you walk through on the door should be "passable" (not Impassable), and twosided (flags = 4).\par \pard \par \li396 The Sidedefs that are on the outside of the door should NOT have a Normal or Lower texture.  They should have an Upper Texture. The Sidedefs on the inside of the door should not have any textures (Normal, Upper, or Lower).\par \pard \par \b Left and Right side of Door\b0 :\par \par \li396 Nothing special here.  You may want to pick a Doorlike texture for the sidedefs like "DOORTRAK".\par \pard \par \page
${\footnote $ [6.2] Lifts}
#{\footnote # LIFTS}
+{\footnote + AN:00002}
K{\footnote K Lifts}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [6.2] Lifts\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 A lift is a sector surrounded by LineDefs with the "Lower lift" or "Raise lift" type.  All LineDefs between the upper floor and the lift will have the "Lower lift" type.  All LineDefs between the lower floor and the lift will have the "Raise lift" type.\par Usually, you also have some "Lower lift" LineDefs on the lower floor, a few steps away from the lift.\par \par The "Raise lift" type is a special case: when you cross this line, the lift will go up.  If the lift is already up, it will act as a switch that lowers the lift.\par \par In the editor, you will see a short line on one side of the LineDef when you select it (this is the normal vector).  In the game, the player must come from this side or else the lift won't work.\par \par Don't forget to give a tag number to the Sector and the LineDefs!\par \par \page
