K{\footnote K Teleporters}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [6.3] Teleporters\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 You need two things to make a teleporter:\par \par \pard \tx756 \fi-360 \li756 \f14 \'b7\f12 \tab \tab One LineDef with the "Teleport" type and a Sector with the same  tag number.\par \f14 \'b7\f12 \tab \tab A special Thing in this sector, called "Teleport exit"/  "Teleport landing".\par \pard \par You may have several LineDefs that point to the same Sector, but you must have one and only one Sector with the same tag number.\par \par This only works if the line is crossed from the right side (see \uldb Lifts\uldb0 \v LIFTS\v0 ). If the teleporter worked on the two sides of the LineDef, you wouldn't be able to exit from it!\par \par \page
${\footnote $ [6.4] Rising stairs}
#{\footnote # Rising_stairs}
+{\footnote + AN:00004}
K{\footnote K Rising stairs}
\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [6.4] Rising stairs\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 A raising staircase is created by defining a set of adjacent sectors at the same elevation. The sector that will be the first (lowest) step is assigned a LineDef tag corresponding to a Linedef of the Raise Stairs type. Each step will raise to an elevation of 8 higher than its next lower neighbor, or 8 up from its original level in the case of the first step.\par \par If we define a set of sectors at an elevation of 0 as shown below:\par \par \f11 \fs18     +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |  1  |  2  |  3  |  4  |  5  |  6  |  7  |  8  |  9  |  A  |\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+\par \f12 \fs24 \par with sector _1_ connected to a Raise Stairs LineDef, the sectors that will form the stairs are those sectors that\par \par \pard \tx756 \fi-360 \li756 1.\tab Are at the same elevation as the first 'step' sector.\par 2.\tab Share a LineDef with a sector that is part of the stairs.\par 3.\tab The _first_ SideDef of the shared LineDef is part of the stairs.\par 4.\tab The shared LineDef has a _lower_ LineDef number than any other LineDef facing 'into' (by condition 3) the previous sector.\par \pard \par For example, if the linedefs were defined as follows:\par \par \pard \tx2835 \f11 \fs18     +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par   --|  1--|  2--|  3--|  4--|  5  |--6--|  7--|  8--|  9--|  A--|\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+\par \f12 \fs24 \par \pard If Sector 1 was the first 'step', then Sectors 2, 3, 4, and 5 would be part of the staircase. Because the LineDef between Sectors 5 and 6 'faces' _away_ from Sector 5, Sector 6 will not raise when the staircase is triggered. If Sector 5 had a Floor elevation of 10, it would not become part of the staircase; only sectors with their Floor levels at the same level as the first step will be part of the staircase, regardless of the 'facing' of the LineDefs connecting them.\par \par The facing of the LineDefs making up the _sides_ of the staircase is important; you can make turning or spiral staircases, but you can also make staircases that elevate the floor of a room instead. Expanding the example, let us assume that Sector 0 is everything surrounding the sectors that are defined:\par \par \f11 \fs18     +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |    b|     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par   --|  1--|  2--|  3--|  4--|  5  |--6--|  7--|  8--|  9--|  A--|     0\par     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |\par     |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |     |     |     |     |\par     +--|--+--|--+--|--+--|--+--|--+--|--+-----+-----+-----+-----+\par        a\par \f12 \fs24 \par Now the LineDefs that make up the lower 'side' of Sectors 1 through 6 'face' into the staircase. If the LineDef number of the LineDef between Sector 1 and Sector 0 (labelled 'a' above) is _lower_ than the LineDef number of the LineDef number of the LineDef between Sector 1 and Sector 2 (labelled 'b' above), then when the stair is triggered, Sectors 1 and 0 will rise, then Sector 0 will rise further. This is not likely to be what you want.\par \par When creating a set of sectors to become an elevating staircase, make sure that either:\par \par \pard \tx756 \fi-360 \li756 a)\tab All the LineDefs _except_ the ones defining the path of the staircase face _away_ from the staircase's sectors, or\par b)\tab The LineDefs defining the path of the staircase, within a Sector, have _lower_ LineDef numbers than any other LineDef facing into that Sector.\par \pard \par The LineDef tag for sectors composing a staircase are, except for the sector that is the first step, irrelevant; the only use for nonzero LineDef tags in any other staircase sector is to have the editor flag the sector in a different color so the user can see where the limits of the staircase are. It is the sector elevation and the LineDef facing that determine the limits\par of a staircase.\par \par \page
