\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [9] Tutorial\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \qc \f12 \b \cf0 WinDEU TUTORIAL v1.5\par \pard \b0 \par \fi-720 \li720 Note:\tab This tutorial was moved into this help file from the TUTOR.DOC file, which comes with DEU.\par \pard \par This document and the accompanying .wad files should help you to see what you need to do to build a level.  It's a sort of touch-and-see how it works thing. (sounds like fun!)\par \par Items appearing in braces \{\} indicate that there is a file that you can load to follow along and see how to do things. All these files can be found in the "TUTOR" directory. See \uldb File|Open wad file \uldb0 \v Open_WAD_file\v0  to know how to load a patch wad file.  After the file is loaded, edit the level (episode 2, mission 1) (See \uldb Editor|Edit level\uldb0 \v Edit_level\v0 ). Then select the \uldb editing mode(s)\uldb0 \v Modes\v0  indicated in the braces and move the pointer around to touch things and look at how they are structured.\par \par \par First go to:\par \tab \uldb Making your first level\uldb0 \v Making_your_first_level\v0 \par \par Now that we have a level, let's put some cool stuff in it.  What we will do here is to show ONE possible way to construct some special sectors like doors, stairs and lifts.  Please note that there ARE other ways to do them because there are many different types of doors & lifts, etc.  Also, you're a little more experienced at making vertices, lines and sectors already so we are not going to have as many WAD files to demonstrate the structures, just one or two to show each structure.\par \par Go to\par \tab \uldb Adding a door\uldb0 \v Adding_a_door\v0 \par \tab \uldb Adding a stairway\uldb0 \v Adding_a_stairway\v0 \par \tab \uldb Adding a lift\uldb0 \v Adding_a_lift\v0 \par \tab \uldb Adding a transporter\uldb0 \v Adding_a_transporter\v0 \par \tab \uldb Texture alignment basis\uldb0 \v Texture_alignment_basis\v0 \par \tab \uldb Complex texture alignment\uldb0 \v Complex_texture_alignment\v0 \par \tab \uldb Upper and lower textures alignment\uldb0 \v Upper_and_lower_textures_alignment\v0 \par \par See also \uldb [6] Special Doom areas\uldb0 \v SPECIAL_DOOM_AREAS\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Making your first level}
#{\footnote # Making_your_first_level}
+{\footnote + AP:00001}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Making your first level\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 This section is divided into 14 steps. Use the WinHELP bowser buttons (<< and >>) when in \uldb step 1\uldb0 \v Step_1\v0  to naviguate.\par \par Now we begin our journey...\par \par Go to \uldb Step 1\uldb0 \v Step_1\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 1}
#{\footnote # Step_1}
+{\footnote + AQ:00001}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 1\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 First create the new map with the Create command from the \uldb Edit|Create\uldb0 \v Create_level\v0  menu item (episode 2, mission 1, for example).  Go into vertices mode (hit \uldb tab\uldb0 \v Change_edit_mode_keys\v0 ) and create some vertices by positioning the cursor where you want the vertex and then press "\uldb Ins\uldb0 \v Insert_object_keys\v0 " to place a vertex there.  Using the Grid mode (press \uldb H\uldb0 \v Grid_keys\v0  to show the grid, then \uldb Shift-H\uldb0 \v Grid_keys\v0  to "snap to grid") is helpful if you want to line up the vertices.  You will need a minimum of three to create an enclosed polygon.  (Don't be afraid of running out until you're really good at this, many doom maps contain well over 800 vertices.)\par \par Go to \uldb Step 2\uldb0 \v Step_2\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 2}
#{\footnote # Step_2}
+{\footnote + AQ:00002}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 2\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Group the vertices by marking them (highlight them and \uldb Shift-left click the mouse\uldb0 \v Mouse_Commands\v0  or press "\uldb M\uldb0 \v Mark_objects_keys\v0 ") and add linedefs by pressing "\uldb Shift-Ins\uldb0 \v Insert_object_keys\v0 ".  It is best to mark them in CLOCKWISE order.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 3\uldb0 \v Step_3\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 3}
#{\footnote # Step_3}
+{\footnote + AQ:00003}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 3\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Mark all of the lines for the sector (you will want to mark the ones that aren't already marked) and press "\uldb Ins\uldb0 \v Insert_object_keys\v0 " to add a closed sector.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 4\uldb0 \v Step_4\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 4}
#{\footnote # Step_4}
+{\footnote + AQ:00004}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 4\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Repeat \uldb step 1\uldb0 \v Step_1\v0 , \uldb step 2\uldb0 \v Step_2\v0  and \uldb step 3\uldb0 \v Step_3\v0 .\par (You'll want more than 1 sector, unless you are very dull).\par \{S1.WAD - vertices, linedefs\}\par Load up this wad and see a very basic 2 sector map.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 5\uldb0 \v Step_5\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 5}
#{\footnote # Step_5}
+{\footnote + AQ:00005}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 5\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 (This step is made mostly obsolete by DEU5.0 and above since it now does these things automatically, but you can verify it anyway.)\par \par If you have any lines that are shared by 2 sectors and are meant to be the place where you cross from room to room set the Flags to 2S (two-sided and shoot thru) and turn off the Impassable Flag. You will probably want to get rid of any of the Normal/Upper/Lower Textures that are on lines that you walk across (usually, unless you want to create the illusion of walking through a wall.).\par \par \{S2.WAD - Linedef\} Check out Linedef # 1.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 6\uldb0 \v Step_6\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 6}
#{\footnote # Step_6}
+{\footnote + AQ:00006}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 6\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 To change the way the walls look, select a line or a group of lines and change the Normal texture on some of the Sidedefs. (To go to \uldb line editing mode\uldb0 \v LineDefs_edit_mode\v0 , press \uldb L\uldb0 \v Change_edit_mode_keys\v0 ).\par \par \{S3.WAD - Linedef\} Take a look at Linedefs #0,2, and 3.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 7\uldb0 \v Step_7\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 7}
#{\footnote # Step_7}
+{\footnote + AQ:00007}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 7\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Change the Floor and Ceiling Textures in a sector. (To go to \uldb sector editing mode\uldb0 \v Sectors_edit_mode\v0 , press \uldb S\uldb0 \v Change_edit_mode_keys\v0 ).\par \par \{s4.wad -Sector\}  Look at Sector #1, compare to the default in sector 0.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 8\uldb0 \v Step_8\v0 .\par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 8}
#{\footnote # Step_8}
+{\footnote + AQ:00008}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 8\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Add a Player1 Start thing. If you want to play cooperatively you will also want to add a Player2, Player3 and Player4 start thing and if you want to play in deathmatch mode you must have a MINIMUM of 4 deathmatch start things. See \uldb Things edit mode\uldb0 \v Things_edit_mode\v0 .\par \par \{s5.wad -Things\}  That's were you start and the direction you're facing.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 9\uldb0 \v Step_9\v0 .\par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 9}
#{\footnote # Step_9}
+{\footnote + AQ:00009}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 9\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Change the type of one of the lines to "Special - Ends level goes to next level." If you want to be able to leave the level you will need an exit. (Even if just to see the deathmatch frag counts!).\par \par \{S6.WAD - Linedefs\} Check out Line 5.  Oh yeah, the texture was changed to one of the SW1xxxx textures so that it looks like a switch too.  Nice touch eh?\par \par Go to \uldb Step 10\uldb0 \v Step_10\v0 .\par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 10}
#{\footnote # Step_10}
+{\footnote + AQ:00010}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 10\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Use \uldb Q\uldb0 \v Quit_key\v0  to quit and save your changes.  Answer Y to the question about building the nodes, etc. (unless you use expert mode, in which case... Why are you reading the tutorial?? ;-)\par \par Go to \uldb Step 11\uldb0 \v Step_11\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 11}
#{\footnote # Step_11}
+{\footnote + AQ:00011}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 11\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Use Q to quit WinDEU.\par Quit Windows (recommended) or go to a DOS box\par \par Go to \uldb Step 12\uldb0 \v Step_12\v0  \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 12}
#{\footnote # Step_12}
+{\footnote + AQ:00012}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 12\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 Fire up doom and try it out! In your doom directory, type:\par \par \li360 DOOM -FILE yourfile.WAD\par \pard \par \li720 If you are working on a level higher than E1M1 you can go straight there by using IDCLEVxy  where x is the episode and y is the mission #.\par \pard \par Go to \uldb Step 13\uldb0 \v Step_13\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 13}
#{\footnote # Step_13}
+{\footnote + AQ:00013}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 13\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 To record a demo of your level (a .LMP file) type this:\par \par \li360 DOOM -DEVPARM -WARP e m -SKILL s -RECORD demofile -FILE yourfile.WAD\par \pard \par You must NOT type the .LMP extention and you MUST type the .WAD extension. 'e' is for Episode (1, 2 or 3), 'm' is for mission (1 to 9) and 's' is for skill level (1 to 5). If you die before the end, press SPACE to end the recording and go back to DOS.\par \par Go to \uldb Step 14\uldb0 \v Step_14\v0 \par \par \page
${\footnote $ Step 14}
#{\footnote # Step_14}
+{\footnote + AQ:00014}
\keepn \f12 \fs24 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i Step 14\par \cf1 \fs24 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \cf0 To play back your demo, type this:\par \par \li360 DOOM -PLAYDEMO demofile -FILE yourfile.WAD \par \pard \par Go to \uldb [9] Tutorial\uldb0 \v Tutorial\v0 \par \par \page
