\keepn \f12 \fs22 \f12 \cf5 \fs36 \b \i [10.2] Doom / WinDEU limits\par \cf1 \fs22 \b0 \i0 \pard \f12 \fs24 \pard \li360 \cf0 Maximum size of a wad file created with WinDEU: This depends on how much windows virtual memory you can free up.  The more free ram, the bigger the WAD can be.  You shouldn't have problem with 2Mb of physical memory.\par \pard \par \li360 X,Y locations of vertices:  somewhere in excess of 10,000 to  +10,000.  It could be 32768 to + 32767.  Note however that WinDEU might get a little weird if your vertices are too far apart.\par \pard \par \li360 Maximum number of sector tags: 255\par \pard \par \li360 Maximum number of enemies/things that can be displayed at a  time: Somewhere near 64.  We've seen that when there are too many some of them will disappear and reappear.  This looks really bad.  \par \pard \par \li360 The doom engine (v1.2) can handle floors & cielings from 32768 to  +32768 as long as the difference in a sector is not more than 1000. DEU imposes a limit of 16384 as a safety feature and will check for the ceiling/floor difference when you run the 'check textures' test.\par \pard \par \li360 The Maximum 2S linedefs that you can see from any point before DOOM engine limit causes HOM (\uldb Hall of Mirrors effect\uldb0 \v HOM_EFFECT\v0 ): Somewhere near 16.\par \pard \par \li360 Maximum stair you can climb: 24 units.\par \pard \par \li360 Minimum floor to ceiling distance that you can walk through:  Near 60 units.\par \pard \par \li360 Minimum wall distance you can squeeze through: 34 units.\par \pard \par \li360 Number of hours playing doom before your spouse (or friend) files a certificate of your death and claims benefits:  Do you really want to find out?  Spend a little quality time with them!\par \pard \par \page
